snippet.textDisplay:
The first sign with problems for A11 was when Niel did the voice over to the launch. Clear and calm, the constant professional, he reported that all systems were nominal (ok).
It was odd because the footage showed the rocket rise into the sky from 3 miles away, and the roar of the engine was powerful even at that distance. The acoustic insulation and isolation from the world outside was better than any sound studio. NASA never boasted about it because that was how it was back then, totally cool.
Infact, being cool was almost the undoing of the crew:
Low earth orbit in the sun is 120°C, and the Apollo's craft wasn't fitted with the solar panels and parasol shields of Skylab or the ISS. You or i would've certainly cooked out in the sun, but the crew were specially picked. They were the coolest out of a very cool generation.
Various reasons why Apollo didnt need shade have been offered by fans, including the shiny skin of aluminium and mylar coating the craft like an oven tray. Other have pointed out the lack of molecules in the very thin skin of the craft, limiting conduction, which is probably a completely different process in space anyway.
The idea of escaping the tether of earths gravity turned out to be wrong. Issac Newton was right about the gravity of Earth holding the moon in place, which is another invaluable contribution from apollo for confirming that.
It turned out that Dr James van Allen had entirely missed the safe passge through his radiation belts too. The crew had more to worry about than to explain any of that, as Neil eloquently said.
"We had more than science to worry about.", he said, on return, possibly wondering why they hadn't first sent a more dispensible ape through that zone first, or how well the photos would turn out after such high altitude work.
So then comes the descent stage, landing onto unprepared ground, untested and sight largely unseen. Nobody knew what the surface they were landing on would be like. There was no way to tell. Would the sink down into a powdery death? Would they land on a pinnacle of rock laid in a shallow powder basin? Was a softlanding going to work on the moon? Afterall, nobody had ever tried it.
Why did he agree to this? How had his bosses sign off on this level of risk?
But it was like that in the 60s, we were all taking life by the short and curlies, even professionals.
Good times.
Getting back into orbit meant that a 2 ton vehicle would need to lift its own wieght 60 miles up and accelerate to 18kmph. And that would be the easy bit. Without any coms satalite- the moon had none at this time, the ascent stage was to intercept an orbitor travelling faster than a bullet- much faster.
To help get it right there were computers everywhere. There was one on the LEM below, one on the ascent stage, one on the orbitor and one at mission control 250k miles away.
These obviously weren't like todays computers. They were dedicated to rocket missions for one thing, which is a great advantage over a gameboym for examplem which would be much good except for killing time.
Unfortunately there was the problem of lag. That's the problem you have today when you are at a busy junction and the satnav waits until too late to instruct you whiich way to go. Well it was like that in the 70s, only worse. So, you imput all the values and velocities and positions and headings, and then about 5 minutes later you get told you missed the turning 4 minutes ago!
(They had no clock driven computers.)
Lickily the crew were adept at making startlingly good estimates, as you can listen to if you go over the old braodcast tapes.
To think anyone still doubts the missions, even when photos have picked out the moontracks made by the missions. Isn't it great that we can pick out our own tracks from the network of tracks covering much of the lunar surface. And we have the mirrors which are at least as reflective as the Russian mission reflectors, how could they have got there if we hadn't landed?

snippet.textDisplay:
Im pretty sure that it is "one small step for man", since he is referencing himself as one single man, in almost a romanticized tone. The "a" in the supposed "a man" is implied. You can play the recording countless times, and you can tell that he doesn't say "a". There is simply not enough time in between "for" and "man" for there to be another word in there, even if we assume that the audio cut out for a split second.


Edit: it turns out that he technically did say "a", but it was undetectable to the human ear. They ran his quote through a certain program, and a 35-millisecond-long bump can be seen, like i said, undetectable to humans. Some people believe this could have been the word "a", and Armstrong just mumbled it, but it could have also been any other form of static coming through. Either way, his quote would have made sense. He is speaking about himself in the third person, where the "a" or "this" is implied, once again, through a more romanticized tone and diction.
